HENRY PROJECT - CORE DEVELOPMENT RULES
1. ARCHITECTURE, MODULARITY & MICROSERVICES
Headless Core & UI Satellites: Henry is transitioning from a monolith to a decoupled microservice architecture. main.py is becoming the central API Core Router running FastAPI (http://localhost:8000). All frontends (Telegram Bot, Browser Extensions, CLI) and background workers are standalone programs that communicate exclusively via HTTP REST-API.

Provider Agnostic: The LLM (Ollama, OpenAI, Anthropic) and Memory systems must be abstracted via protocols. Swapping or routing between providers must only require a config change in providers.yaml.

Strict Separation of Concerns: Background Workers (like the OCR Watcher in tools/file_manager.py) must handle only their specialized task. They MUST NOT contain Telegram-bot logic or direct database connections. They execute their task and send JSON payloads to the Core API (/v1/process).

No Legacy Leftovers: When extracting features into standalone programs, completely strip out old internal callbacks and unneeded manager imports. Provide a clean if __name__ == "__main__": block for independent terminal testing.

Clean Code: PEP 8, typing hints (from __future__ import annotations), small functions, and clear headers.

2. SECURITY, STORAGE & PRIVACY
Encrypted Volume Shield: The Core must strictly check if the encrypted volume under MEMORY_MOUNT_PATH (e.g., /Volumes/HenryData/) is active. If offline, the system must set SECURITY_FLIGHT_MODE = True, block all database writes (ChromaDB/SQLite), and run in a volatile safe mode to prevent PII leaks to the local SSD.

Anonymization Schleuse: A local Presidio PII shield must inspect and mask sensitive data before the multi-model router evaluates cloud-based routing scores. Unencrypted cleartext must never leave the local environment.

OrbStack / Docker Ready: All standalone services must be fully containerizable via OrbStack, utilizing environment variables (.env) and network isolation.

3. PROMPT & ROUTING LOGIC
Global Rules: Respect config/global_rules.yaml (short, concise, honest).

Multi-Model Scoring: The core routing engine dynamically routes queries based on a weighted matrix analyzing capability, privacy, cost, and latency.

4. GITHUB WORKFLOW
Explain your Work: Every PR must contain a "What, Why & Security Impact" summary.

Review Loop: Use separate branches; never push directly to main. Incremental, step-by-step refactoring only.